# VPN and Proxy Servers

## Objective
To understand what a VPN and a proxy server are and how 
they help in securing internal networks.

## What is a VPN?
A VPN stands for Virtual Private Network. It is a network 
security service that changes our public IP address and 
hides our virtual location on the internet.

## How a VPN Works
A VPN works by creating an encrypted tunnel between our 
device and a VPN server. All our internet traffic passes 
through this tunnel, hiding our data from anyone trying 
to intercept it, including our internet service provider.

## Types of VPNs
- **Remote Access VPN** — used by individuals to establish 
a connection between a personal device and a VPN server
- **Site-to-Site VPN** — used by enterprises to extend 
their network to other locations

## VPN Protocols
- **WireGuard** — a modern, fast VPN protocol
- **IPSec** — encrypts traffic over a secure network tunnel

## What is a Proxy Server?
A proxy server is a server that fulfils requests by 
forwarding them to other servers. It acts as a middleman 
between a user and the internet.

## How a Proxy Server Works
When you send a request, it goes to the proxy server first. 
The proxy then forwards it to the destination server on 
your behalf, hiding your real IP address in the process.

## Types of Proxy Servers
- **Forward Proxy** — restricts a person's access to 
the internet
- **Reverse Proxy** — restricts the internet's access 
to an internal server
- **Email Proxy** — filters spam emails by checking 
the sender's address

## VPN vs Proxy — Key Differences
| | VPN | Proxy |
|---|---|---|
| Encrypts traffic | Yes | No |
| Hides IP address | Yes | Yes |
| Covers all traffic | Yes | Usually one app only |
| Best for | Privacy and security | Controlling access |

## Why They Matter for Cybersecurity
VPNs and proxy servers are important security tools because 
they encrypt data and packets, hide user identities, and 
safeguard internal servers from outside access.

## Key Takeaways
- VPNs provide strong privacy and encryption for all traffic
- Proxy servers control and filter network requests
- Both tools help protect internal networks but in 
different ways

